## Refinancing: When It Makes Sense (and When It Doesn't)

Refinancing replaces your existing loans with a new private loan at (ideally) a lower interest rate. This can save money — but it comes with a massive caveat.

**When you refinance federal loans, they become private.** You permanently lose:
- IDR eligibility
- PSLF eligibility
- Deferment/forbearance protections
- All forgiveness pathways

Refinancing only makes sense if: you have private loans (nothing to lose), you have high-interest federal loans with no intention of pursuing forgiveness, you have a strong credit score qualifying you for a significantly lower rate, and your job situation is stable.

Don't refinance federal loans if you're pursuing PSLF, planning to use IDR, have an unstable income, or might need deferment.

## One Actionable Step Today

Log into StudentAid.gov and review your federal loan balance, servicer, and current repayment plan. Many borrowers don't know what plan they're on or haven't re-enrolled after the COVID pause.

If you're unsure whether IDR or standard repayment is better for your situation, a nonprofit credit counselor can run the numbers for free.

